# Virtual Machine I: Stack Arithmetic

The Virtual Machine (VM) is an intermediate layer between high-level languages and the Hack platform. It models a stack-based computer, making it easy to compile to and simple to translate to assembly.

## The Stack Model

A stack is a LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) data structure with two fundamental operations:
- **push** — place a value on top
- **pop** — remove the top value

The VM uses a stack for all arithmetic and logical operations:

```
push 5          push 3          add
[ ]             [ ]             [ ]
[ ]             [ ]             [ ]
[ ]             [ ]             [ ]
[5]             [3]             [8]
                [5]
```

## VM Arithmetic Commands

| Command     | Effect                    |
|-------------|---------------------------|
| add         | pop x, pop y, push y+x   |
| sub         | pop x, pop y, push y-x   |
| neg         | pop x, push -x           |
| eq          | pop x, pop y, push (y==x)|
| gt          | pop x, pop y, push (y>x) |
| lt          | pop x, pop y, push (y<x) |
| and         | pop x, pop y, push y&x   |
| or          | pop x, pop y, push y|x   |
| not         | pop x, push !x           |

## Memory Segments

The VM also handles memory access through named segments:

| Segment    | Purpose                       | Mapped to        |
|------------|-------------------------------|------------------|
| constant   | constant values 0-32767       | built-in         |
| argument   | function arguments            | RAM[ARG]+offset  |
| local      | local variables               | RAM[LCL]+offset  |
| static     | global static variables       | RAM[16+offset]   |
| this/that  | pointer-based heap access     | RAM[THIS/THAT]+offset |
| temp       | temporary storage (8 slots)   | RAM[5+offset]    |
| pointer    | access THIS/THAT registers    | RAM[3+offset]    |

## Push and Pop Implementation

Each VM command translates to several assembly instructions. For example:

```
push constant 5
// becomes:
@5              // A = 5
D=A             // D = 5
@SP             // A = stack pointer address
A=M             // A = current stack top
M=D             // write value to stack
@SP             // increment SP
M=M+1
```

