A visual explanation of stack-based virtual machines and how they bridge high-level languages and hardware.
:::

## Think Critically

:::evaluate{criteria="stack-vs-register"}

### Stack VM vs. Register VM

The Hack VM uses a stack architecture (like the JVM), while real CPUs typically use registers. What are the trade-offs? Why might a course project choose a stack VM?

### Criteria
- Identifies stack VM simplicity for code generation
- Notes performance trade-off (more instructions needed)
- Explains compiler-friendliness of stack-based intermediate representation
:::

## Project

:::project{environment="node" template="nand2tetris-project7"}

### Objective

Build the first part of the VM translator: translate stack arithmetic and memory access commands into Hack assembly.

### Requirements
1. Implement the Parser (reads VM commands, strips comments/whitespace)
2. Implement the CodeWriter (generates assembly for push/pop and arithmetic/logical commands)
3. Support all memory segments: constant, argument, local, static, this, that, temp, pointer
4. Support all arithmetic/logical commands: add, sub, neg, eq, gt, lt, and, or, not
5. Test with the supplied .vm programs using the CPU Emulator

### Hints
- The stack pointer SP is at RAM[0]
- The eq/gt/lt commands require conditional branching in assembly
- Use the built-in VM Emulator to debug your VM programs before testing your translator
:::
